<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-02-12T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-02-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="387" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d387">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 837.61351/114a</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Consul General at Habana</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Harris</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-02-12">
                                        <hi rend="italic">February 12, 1918</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>For Consul General Morgan:<note n="1" xml:id="d387fn1">On detail as
                                    special agent in Cuba.</note>
                                <quote rend="blockquote">
                                    <p>With regard to the 25 per cent of uncontracted sugar you can
                                        say that as long as the war lasts we are not going to allow
                                        the import of sugar into the United States at one penny
                                        variation from the agreed price inasmuch as the whole of the
                                        sugar that is not taken by the Allies will be needed for
                                        American consumption. This should be sufficient assurance to
                                        the producer. We are making every possible effort to
                                        complete the loan at earliest moment. Yesterday some
                                        $45,000,000 were subscribed and further meetings of bankers
                                        in New York, Boston, and Philadelphia are being held with
                                        view to completing the amount, and the Cuban Government
                                        should necessarily implement all of their resources and
                                        credit to handle this situation which is practically one of
                                        domestic order and in which we are only intervening out of
                                        desire to be of service to the Cuban people.</p>
                                    <p rend="right">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Herbert Hoover</hi>
                                    </p>
                                </quote>
                            </p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>